{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16165"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16165"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.01,0.9,0,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8856"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16165"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96375"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"3162"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46368"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by her sister with concerns about her behaviour over the past two weeks. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her sister reports that she has been sleeping less than three hours per night and seems \u0027full of energy\u0027. When asked about her sleeping difficulties, the patient responds: \u0027Sleep is like clouds in the sky, and the clouds remind me of my childhood when I used to lie in the grass, which is why I\u0027ve been thinking about starting a landscaping business, even though I\u0027ve never done gardening before, but I read that green is a healing colour, and healing is important because there\u0027s so much suffering in the world, like those poor penguins affected by climate change.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears restless and is speaking rapidly. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Schizophrenia","Delirium","Manic episode","Generalised anxiety disorder","Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a manic episode, including markedly decreased need for sleep (less than three hours per night), increased energy, psychomotor agitation, pressured speech, and disorganised thinking patterns. The two-week duration meets the diagnostic criteria for a manic episode, which requires symptoms lasting at least one week (or any duration if hospitalisation is necessary).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManic episode\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the constellation of symptoms. The patient demonstrates the cardinal features of mania: elevated energy despite minimal sleep, rapid speech, psychomotor restlessness, and potentially risky behaviour (planning to start a business with no experience). Her thought pattern shows distractibility and racing thoughts, moving rapidly from one topic to another. These symptoms represent a clear change from her baseline functioning and are causing concern to her family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with positive symptoms (hallucinations, delusions) and negative symptoms (social withdrawal, flat affect, alogia) that develop over at least one month. While disorganised speech can occur in schizophrenia, this patient\u0027s presentation is dominated by mood symptoms and increased goal-directed activity rather than psychotic features. The acute onset over two weeks and the prominence of mood symptoms make schizophrenia less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by an acute confusional state with fluctuating consciousness, inattention, and disorganised thinking. While delirium can cause sleep disturbance and agitation, patients typically show impaired consciousness and cognitive deficits. This patient appears alert and oriented, with no mention of fluctuating consciousness or cognitive impairment. The absence of an underlying medical cause or medication trigger also makes delirium unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves excessive worry and anxiety about multiple areas of life for at least six months. While anxiety can cause sleep disturbance and restlessness, it does not typically cause the decreased need for sleep (feeling rested despite minimal sleep), grandiosity, or pressured speech seen in this patient. The acute onset and severity of symptoms are not consistent with generalised anxiety disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttention deficit hyperactivity disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is a neurodevelopmental disorder with onset in childhood, characterised by persistent patterns of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity. While ADHD can cause restlessness and distractibility, it does not cause the episodic mood changes, decreased need for sleep, or grandiose thinking seen in this patient. The acute onset in adulthood without any childhood history makes ADHD highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient will require urgent psychiatric assessment and likely admission for treatment of her manic episode. Initial management typically includes mood stabilisers or antipsychotic medications, along with ensuring safety and addressing any immediate risks associated with impaired judgement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Manic episodes are characterised by elevated mood, decreased need for sleep, increased energy, and rapid speech lasting at least one week.","Bipolar disorder requires at least one manic or hypomanic episode, distinguishing it from major depressive disorder.","Acute psychotic symptoms can occur during manic episodes but resolve with treatment of the underlying mood disorder."],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry.","Bloch S, Green SA, Janca A, Mitchell PB, Roberston M. Foundations of Clinical Psychiatry. Chapter 16: Schizophrenia and Related Disorders. Melbourne University Press; 2017.","Hitczenko K, Mittal VA, Goldrick M. Understanding Language Abnormalities and Associated Clinical Markers in Psychosis: The Promise of Computational Methods. Schizophr Bull. 2021 Mar 16;47(2):344-362. doi: 10.1093/schbul/sbaa141. PMID: 33205155; PMCID: PMC8480175."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96375"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16165"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96375"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T07:39:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T07:49:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8856"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap